Graphical Analysis

We start with some basic graphical analysis to understand the data.

Error rate

The error rate seems quite uniformly distributed. Given our small sample (only 45 cases), this has as advantage that we have examples for any error_rate we want, but the disadvantage is that we have only one example for most cases. The latter can later be fixed, by building appropriate examples from the hypotheses we generate.

Depth

Letâs start from the obvious measure: does the depth influence the error rate?

Visually, it doesnât look like depth is a relevant factor. What about qubits and clbits?

Here we start to see a difference (good!), but note that the data seems the same for qubits and clbits. Control:

nrow(qdata[qdata$qubits != qdata$clbits, ])
## [1] 0

For now, we simply analyse in relation to qubits. A simple linear regression model seems adequate.

lm_fit <- lm(error_rate ~ qubits, data=qdata)
summary(lm_fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = error_rate ~ qubits, data = qdata)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -0.27711 -0.09091 -0.02754  0.10441  0.36612 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  -0.2447     0.0700  -3.496  0.00111 ** 
## qubits        0.1607     0.0165   9.740 1.91e-12 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.1565 on 43 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6881, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6808 
## F-statistic: 94.86 on 1 and 43 DF,  p-value: 1.909e-12
plot(lm_fit$residuals, pch = 16, col = "red")

Indeed, the residuals do not have a pattern, but the R2 is not very good: 0.6881001. Still, there is wide variability, and we see that qubits is a good predictor for error. Other details may be necessary.
